STEP 1: Create Jenkins Job
- Open Jenkins Dashboard
- Click "New Item"
- Enter name: Docker Integration with Jenkins
- Select "Freestyle project"
- Click OK

STEP 2: Configure Job
- In "Source Code Management":
  → Select Git
  → Paste your GitHub repository URL (which contains Dockerfile & Java file)
- In "Build Triggers":
  → Select as needed (e.g., GitHub hook trigger or manual build)
- In "Build Environment":
  → Configure as required

STEP 3: Create GitHub Repository
- Create a new repository in GitHub
- Add the following files:
  → Dockerfile
  → Java file (e.g., Main.java)

Sample Java File (Main.java):
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Hello from Docker + Jenkins!");
    }
}

Sample Dockerfile:
FROM openjdk:17
WORKDIR /app
COPY Main.java .
RUN javac Main.java
CMD ["java", "Main"]

STEP 4: Add Build Commands in Jenkins
- Go to "Build" section
- Click "Add build step"
- Select "Execute Windows batch command"
- Add the following commands:

docker build -t java-app .
docker run -d -t java-app

STEP 5: Save & Build
- Click "Save"
- Click "Build Now"

STEP 6: Verify Output
- Check Console Output in Jenkins (should show success)
- Open Docker Desktop or run:
  docker images
  docker ps

You should see:
- Image: java-app
- Running container (if build is successful)
